Open in new tab
Results
Differences in the light and hydrostatic environment by canopy type

Light increased exponentially with height within both the closed canopy and the exposed canopy (Figure 2 a). We observed marked differences in the light environment (DIFN %) between the closed canopy and the exposed canopy at greater heights (Figure 2 a). Above 10 m in height, we observed an abrupt increase in light with height at the exposed canopy relative to the closed canopy (Figure 2 a). The ANCOVA indicated significant height and canopy-type effects on (ln)light and a significant height × canopy-type interaction (Table 2 ). The intercept of the relationship between (ln)light and height was significantly smaller at the exposed canopy compared with the closed canopy ( P  < 0.001). The relationship between height and Ψ Pre was negatively linear for both canopy types (Figure 2 b). There was a significant height and canopy-type effect on Ψ Pre but the interaction height ×  Ψ Pre was not significant ( P  = 0.993, Table 2 ). Predawn water potential declined by 0.011 MPa per meter increase in height. The intercept of Ψ Pre –height relationships at the closed canopy (−0.19 MPa) was significantly greater than the intercept at the exposed canopy (−0.29 MPa, P  < 0.001).
Figure 2.
Relationships between light and height (a) and ΨPre and height (b) at two canopy types: closed canopy and exposed canopy. Regression models: (a) closed canopy, DIFN = −0.124 + 0.164 × exp(0.033 × height); exposed canopy, DIFN = −0.071 + 0.038 × exp(0.151 × height); and (b) closed canopy, ΨPre = −0.190 − 0.011 × height; exposed canopy, ΨPre = −0.288 − 0.011 × height.
Open in new tab Download slide

Relationships between light and height (a) and Ψ Pre and height (b) at two canopy types: closed canopy and exposed canopy. Regression models: (a) closed canopy, DIFN = −0.124 + 0.164 × exp (0.033 × height) ; exposed canopy, DIFN = −0.071 + 0.038 × exp (0.151 × height) ; and (b) closed canopy, Ψ Pre  = −0.190 − 0.011 × height; exposed canopy, Ψ Pre  = −0.288 − 0.011 × height.
Figure 2.
Relationships between light and height (a) and ΨPre and height (b) at two canopy types: closed canopy and exposed canopy. Regression models: (a) closed canopy, DIFN = −0.124 + 0.164 × exp(0.033 × height); exposed canopy, DIFN = −0.071 + 0.038 × exp(0.151 × height); and (b) closed canopy, ΨPre = −0.190 − 0.011 × height; exposed canopy, ΨPre = −0.288 − 0.011 × height.
Open in new tab Download slide

Relationships between light and height (a) and Ψ Pre and height (b) at two canopy types: closed canopy and exposed canopy. Regression models: (a) closed canopy, DIFN = −0.124 + 0.164 × exp (0.033 × height) ; exposed canopy, DIFN = −0.071 + 0.038 × exp (0.151 × height) ; and (b) closed canopy, Ψ Pre  = −0.190 − 0.011 × height; exposed canopy, Ψ Pre  = −0.288 − 0.011 × height.
Leaf mass per area relationships with height, light and Ψ Pre

Leaf mass per area increased exponentially with height (Figure 3 a). Above 10 m, the trend lines diverge and leaves within the exposed canopy had greater LMA than the closed canopy (Figure 3 a). The ANCOVA indicated significant height, canopy type and interaction (height × canopy type) effects on (ln)LMA (Table 3 ). The relationship between LMA and light was log-linear, and the increase in LMA with increasing light availability was most pronounced at low light (<25% DIFN, Figure 3 b). Above 25% DIFN, the increase in LMA with light was greater within the exposed canopy than the closed canopy (Figure 3 b). We observed significant (ln)light, canopy type and interaction [ln(light) × canopy type] effects on (ln)LMA (Table 3 ). Leaf mass per area exponentially decreased with Ψ Pre (Figure 3 c). There were significant Ψ Pre , canopy type and interaction ( Ψ Pre  × canopy type) effects on (ln)LMA (Table 3 ). Intercepts were significantly different between canopy types for relationships between (ln)LMA and height, (ln)light and Ψ Pre ( P  < 0.01). (ln)Light explained more variation in (ln)LMA than for Ψ Pre for the closed canopy and the exposed canopy (Table 4 ). Based on partial R 2 values, adding ln(light) to the Ψ Pre models showed a 0.15–0.44 increase in R 2 over the Ψ Pre model, whereas adding Ψ Pre to the ln(light) model showed only a 0.05 increase in R 2 over the ln(light) model (Table 4 ). In our post hoc analysis of LMA values collected in August at both the exposed and closed canopy at 17–21 m, we found that mean LMA at the exposed canopy was significantly greater ( P  < 0.001, F  = 267) than LMA at the closed canopy.
Figure 3.
Relationships between LMA and height (a), light (b) and ΨPre (c) at closed canopy and exposed canopy. Regression models: (a) closed canopy, LMA = 15.919 + 13.564 × exp(0.050 × height); exposed canopy, LMA = 0.539 + 19.077 × exp(0.078 × height); (b) closed canopy, LMA = 73.004 + 13.889 × (ln)DIFN; exposed canopy, LMA = 97.334 + 21.521 × (ln)DIFN; and (c) closed canopy, LMA = 23.425 × exp(−1.796 × ΨPre); exposed canopy, LMA = 20.114 × exp(−2.354×ΨPre).
Open in new tab Download slide

Relationships between LMA and height (a), light (b) and Ψ Pre (c) at closed canopy and exposed canopy. Regression models: (a) closed canopy, LMA = 15.919 + 13.564 × exp (0.050 × height) ; exposed canopy, LMA = 0.539 + 19.077 × exp (0.078 × height) ; (b) closed canopy, LMA = 73.004 + 13.889 × (ln)DIFN; exposed canopy, LMA = 97.334 + 21.521 × (ln)DIFN; and (c) closed canopy, LMA = 23.425 × exp ( − 1.796 ×  Ψ Pre ) ; exposed canopy, LMA = 20.114 × exp ( − 2.354× Ψ Pre ) .
Figure 3.
Relationships between LMA and height (a), light (b) and ΨPre (c) at closed canopy and exposed canopy. Regression models: (a) closed canopy, LMA = 15.919 + 13.564 × exp(0.050 × height); exposed canopy, LMA = 0.539 + 19.077 × exp(0.078 × height); (b) closed canopy, LMA = 73.004 + 13.889 × (ln)DIFN; exposed canopy, LMA = 97.334 + 21.521 × (ln)DIFN; and (c) closed canopy, LMA = 23.425 × exp(−1.796 × ΨPre); exposed canopy, LMA = 20.114 × exp(−2.354×ΨPre).
Open in new tab Download slide

Relationships between LMA and height (a), light (b) and Ψ Pre (c) at closed canopy and exposed canopy. Regression models: (a) closed canopy, LMA = 15.919 + 13.564 × exp (0.050 × height) ; exposed canopy, LMA = 0.539 + 19.077 × exp (0.078 × height) ; (b) closed canopy, LMA = 73.004 + 13.889 × (ln)DIFN; exposed canopy, LMA = 97.334 + 21.521 × (ln)DIFN; and (c) closed canopy, LMA = 23.425 × exp ( − 1.796 ×  Ψ Pre ) ; exposed canopy, LMA = 20.114 × exp ( − 2.354× Ψ Pre ) .
Thickness and density

Density displayed similar trends with height, light and Ψ Pre among canopy types to those observed for LMA (Figure 4 ). Leaf density exponentially increased with height, displayed a log-linear increase with light and exponentially decreased with Ψ Pre (Figure 4 ). The main effects [height, (ln)light, Ψ Pre and canopy type] and interaction terms [(height × canopy type, ln(light) × canopy type, Ψ Pre  × canopy type)] were all significant explanatory variables for (ln)density (Table 3 ). Intercepts were significantly different ( P  < 0.001) for (ln)density–(ln)light relationships, but not for height ( P  = 0.35) and Ψ Pre ( P  = 0.26). Partial R 2 values for adding (ln)light (0.08–0.36) to the full model for predicting (ln)density were greater compared with adding Ψ Pre (0.03–0.07, Table 4 ).
